body:
any idea how we want to truncate?  Its super easy to just do something like chopping off all the characters after some size N.  What I've seen to be pretty popular is to have something like "myreallylongteststringtotruncate" be turned into something like "myreallylong...ncate". 

Since our current padding max length for package name is 70 characters, we can reserve say, 67 for the name (to give a 3 space padding between the end of the name and the start of the publish state field) and then break up the same such that we do something like always printing the first 54 characters, 3 periods, and then the last 10 characters of the string.

@dubeejw

if you can wrap your value with quotes, you can preserve the value as a string.

```
> wsk action create echo tests/dat/actions/echo.js
ok: created action echo
> wsk action invoke echo -r -p p 1234 
{
    "p": 1234
}
> wsk action invoke echo -r -p p '"1234"'
{
    "p": "1234"
}
```

That approach doesn't seem to work in the context of bash environment variable substitution:

```
$ wsk action create test3 --docker user/container --param AccountId '"$AccountId"'
$ wsk action get test3
ok: got action test3
{

    "parameters": [
        {
            "key": "AccountId",
            "value": "$AccountId"
        }
    ],
   }
```

That worked for me!

```
$ export AccountId='"1234"'
$ wsk action create test5 --docker user/container --param AccountId "$AccountId"
$ wsk action get test5
{
    "parameters": [
        {
            "key": "AccountId",
            "value": "1234"
        }
    ],
}
```

@mdeuser, I suggest we keep this pr change, since as you see the MakeWskErrorFromWskError was designed to handle err pointers, the error was in essence is string. Nevertheless, It's up to you decide.

Yes I'll create another PR about the const change.
Anyway, thank you guys for help clarify and review. Appreciate it.
